explanation:
To decide whether any operation in OS_mv is dead code you must know whether each call can have differing observable effects (return values or side effects) in some real execution. The following symbols are required and why:

- OS_rename: Directly called by OS_mv; its possible return values determine whether the fallback copy/remove path is ever executed. If OS_rename always succeeds or always fails in the project, then one branch could be dead.

- OS_cp: Directly called as the fallback. You must know whether OS_cp can succeed when OS_rename fails (i.e. whether copy+remove is a viable alternative) and what side effects it produces, to determine if the copy/remove operations are necessary (not dead).

- OS_remove: Called after a successful copy. Its side effects (file removal) are observable and necessary to complete the move semantics; you must know whether it actually does anything in practice and under what conditions it is reached.

- OS_SUCCESS: The constant used to test success. Its definition/value and any related status codes are needed to interpret return_code comparisons and to reason about which branches execute.

- OS_FileRename_Impl: The lower-level rename implementation can contain platform- or filesystem-specific behavior (e.g. fails across filesystems). Understanding its semantics is necessary to determine whether OS_rename can both succeed and fail in real scenarios (i.e. whether the fallback path is ever required).

- OS_FileRemove_Impl: The low-level remove implementation determines whether OS_remove actually removes the file (observable effect) and under what conditions it can fail or be a no-op.

- OS_OpenCreate, OS_read, OS_write, OS_close: Core primitives used by OS_cp (per the call graph). To reason if OS_cp is meaningful (has observable effects) or could be effectively a no-op in the project, you need the behavior (success/failure modes and side effects) of the file I/O operations that implement copying.

- UT_Stub_RegisterReturnType, UT_Stub_RegisterContextWithMetaData, UT_ExecuteBasicHandler, UT_Stub_GetReturnValuePtr: These unit-test stub framework symbols appear in the call graph and can be used in tests to force particular return values or replace implementations. For a correct dead-code analysis you must distinguish production behavior from test-induced behavior — test stubs can make code appear dead in tests (always returning a fixed value) even though it is reachable/observable in production. Therefore the test-stub symbols must be considered to avoid false positives/negatives when assessing dead code.

In short: you need the declarations/implementations (and documented semantics) of the three primary calls and their success code, the lower-level implementations that determine platform-specific behavior, the file-I/O routines used by the copy path, and the unit-test stub machinery that can alter observed behavior in test builds.
